WEBVTT

1
00:00:11.186 --> 00:00:12.354
[knocks on door]

2
00:00:12.438 --> 00:00:13.439
Shit.

3
00:00:16.316 --> 00:00:17.526
[blows]

4
00:00:28.203 --> 00:00:30.539
- Hey. Finally on my way home.
- Hi.

5
00:00:30.622 --> 00:00:32.248
Just wanted to check in.

6
00:00:32.331 --> 00:00:34.668
- Big day today.
- Yeah. it was.

7
00:00:35.419 --> 00:00:37.504
- All good?
- Yeah.

8
00:00:38.005 --> 00:00:39.840
You did well at the Council.

9
00:00:40.507 --> 00:00:42.593
I think it's the start
of something special.

10
00:00:44.261 --> 00:00:46.180
It smells like smoke in here.

11
00:00:49.099 --> 00:00:54.480
Oh. Oh. I… I didn't like the soup.
so I. uh. reheated some pizza.

12
00:00:56.440 --> 00:00:57.733
Okay. well…

13
00:00:57.816 --> 00:00:59.234
- Night.
- Night.

14
00:01:04.947 --> 00:01:06.283
[sighs]

15
00:01:16.376 --> 00:01:19.213
[The Algorithm] The note itself
is not of grave concern.

16
00:01:20.088 --> 00:01:23.967
What is of concern is her decision
to lie to you about it.

17
00:01:25.344 --> 00:01:28.180
The medication can only erase what was.

18
00:01:29.014 --> 00:01:31.725
but if she does not trust
the new narrative.

19
00:01:31.809 --> 00:01:33.519
we have a very different problem.

20
00:01:34.311 --> 00:01:37.940
And you. Camille.
are the narrator she needs to trust.

21
00:01:38.482 --> 00:01:41.568
I don't understand
why this is taking so long.

22
00:01:42.444 --> 00:01:45.030
You said a month. two at most.

23
00:01:45.781 --> 00:01:48.367
[The Algorithm] We have 352 years of data

24
00:01:48.450 --> 00:01:51.662
which demonstrates
the protocol is effective.

25
00:01:51.745 --> 00:01:53.122
Most of the time.

26
00:01:53.205 --> 00:01:54.957
When implemented correctly.

27
00:01:55.749 --> 00:02:02.381
Six silos have successfully undergone full
resets. including your own 140 years ago.

28
00:02:02.464 --> 00:02:05.759
And there have been
individuals targeted along the way.

29
00:02:08.219 --> 00:02:09.805
Your frustration is noted.

30
00:02:11.181 --> 00:02:13.183
While it has largely proven effective.

31
00:02:13.267 --> 00:02:15.310
there have also been exceptions.

32
00:02:15.394 --> 00:02:19.565
Outliers like Juliette Nichols who
have required extended treatment.

33
00:02:19.648 --> 00:02:22.693
You. Camille.
are working with such an outlier.

34
00:02:22.776 --> 00:02:24.695
I feel so much better now.

35
00:02:25.863 --> 00:02:28.323
[The Algorithm] Her dream indicates
some memory of her return

36
00:02:28.407 --> 00:02:29.825
remains in her unconscious.

37
00:02:31.160 --> 00:02:33.996
Continue the medication protocol
for two more weeks.

38
00:02:34.621 --> 00:02:37.916
Tighten her security detail
and double your efforts

39
00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:41.795
to assure Nichols that you are
her most trusted ally.

40
00:02:43.755 --> 00:02:45.757
[Daniel] Thirty miles out of Cartersville.

41
00:02:46.383 --> 00:02:49.428
Kick-ass view of the sunset
over Pine Mountain.

42
00:02:50.721 --> 00:02:56.226
Yeah. we had. um.
horses and ducks and goats.

43
00:02:58.979 --> 00:03:00.355
These two bulldogs.

44
00:03:02.232 --> 00:03:04.359
Angriest dogs God put on the earth.

45
00:03:04.443 --> 00:03:07.321
Only thing they ever did was
chase us from the front gate

46
00:03:07.404 --> 00:03:09.281
to the house every
time we got off the bus.

47
00:03:11.784 --> 00:03:12.785
[chuckles]

48
00:03:13.368 --> 00:03:14.369
[sniffles]

49
00:03:14.453 --> 00:03:19.708
When I told you I-I'd been made the. uh.
University of Georgia Bulldogs' mascot…

50
00:03:23.170 --> 00:03:24.171
Uh. don't…

51
00:03:24.254 --> 00:03:25.255
Don't worry.

52
00:03:26.006 --> 00:03:27.341
What?

53
00:03:27.424 --> 00:03:29.802
Uh. well. you laughed so hard that you…

54
00:03:31.678 --> 00:03:33.305
you pissed yourself. [chuckles]

55
00:03:33.388 --> 00:03:37.810
[chuckles] I don't sound
like a very nice sister.

56
00:03:37.893 --> 00:03:39.019
[sighs]

57
00:03:41.063 --> 00:03:45.818
Mom's name was Grace.

58
00:03:46.485 --> 00:03:47.528
Dad…

59
00:03:49.279 --> 00:03:50.322
William.

60
00:03:51.865 --> 00:03:52.991
Please. I'm…

61
00:03:53.075 --> 00:03:56.120
I-I'm sorry. Donald. I just…

62
00:03:56.620 --> 00:03:57.871
don't know what to say.

63
00:03:57.955 --> 00:03:59.957
No. Um… Um…

64
00:04:02.668 --> 00:04:05.504
- Um. no. Uh. don't be sorry. I'm sorry.
- Um…

65
00:04:05.587 --> 00:04:09.341
- [intercom beeps]
- [announcement. indistinct]

66
00:04:22.771 --> 00:04:23.814
[beeps]

67
00:04:28.777 --> 00:04:30.654
[grunts] Fuck.

68
00:04:32.072 --> 00:04:33.699
- [grunts]
- [doctor] You all right?

69
00:04:33.782 --> 00:04:35.993
I don't usually swear
at inanimate objects.

70
00:04:36.076 --> 00:04:38.287
[doctor] Ah. worse targets for rage.

71
00:04:38.370 --> 00:04:40.914
Besides. this machine's
been asking for it for months.

72
00:04:42.124 --> 00:04:44.501
Mmm. [chews] That's good.

73
00:04:44.585 --> 00:04:46.295
Don't worry about that.

74
00:04:47.004 --> 00:04:48.338
Everything okay?

75
00:04:49.590 --> 00:04:51.216
Yeah. My sister's here.

76
00:04:52.634 --> 00:04:53.969
Well. her body's here.

77
00:04:54.678 --> 00:04:57.514
I'm sitting there with someone
I've spoken to every day for the last

78
00:04:57.598 --> 00:05:01.018
three decades and she's looking
at me like I'm the Uber driver.

79
00:05:01.685 --> 00:05:02.686
You're Daniel.

80
00:05:02.770 --> 00:05:05.564
We've been expecting you.
I'm Victor Crnkovich.

81
00:05:06.190 --> 00:05:08.108
- I'm Charlotte's doctor.
- Oh.

82
00:05:08.192 --> 00:05:09.777
- Hi.
- Um. hi.

83
00:05:09.860 --> 00:05:11.153
It's good to meet you.

84
00:05:11.236 --> 00:05:13.989
Yeah. I'm afraid to tell you that I'm
the reason she doesn't remember you.

85
00:07:11.190 --> 00:07:12.983
[Victor] So. the medication.

86
00:07:13.650 --> 00:07:17.196
i-it's like installing a drawbridge
between her and her memory.

87
00:07:17.279 --> 00:07:20.616
A safety gap. if you will.
between upstairs and downstairs.

88
00:07:20.699 --> 00:07:24.036
Used for too long. the bridge stays up.
becomes permanent

89
00:07:24.119 --> 00:07:25.537
and she never gets her memory back.

90
00:07:25.621 --> 00:07:29.291
But when she's stronger.
we'll pause the medication.

91
00:07:29.374 --> 00:07:32.002
lower the bridge. go across. and choose…

92
00:07:32.085 --> 00:07:33.545
actually choose…

93
00:07:33.629 --> 00:07:36.048
what memories to bring back.
and what to leave behind.

94
00:07:40.719 --> 00:07:41.929
[sighs]

95
00:07:45.432 --> 00:07:48.727
I lost you with the drawbridge thing?

96
00:07:48.811 --> 00:07:49.812
No.

97
00:07:51.063 --> 00:07:52.731
I-I don't know. Yes. uh…

98
00:07:53.524 --> 00:07:55.484
This kind of conversation
wa-wasn't on my list

99
00:07:55.567 --> 00:07:57.236
of things to try to get
my head around today.

100
00:07:58.320 --> 00:08:01.740
The drawbridge comes down.
how do you get her memories back?

101
00:08:01.824 --> 00:08:03.826
We tell her story. over and over.

102
00:08:04.451 --> 00:08:05.577
Her story?

103
00:08:06.370 --> 00:08:07.371
Okay.

104
00:08:08.330 --> 00:08:14.169
[grunts] Why do humans
rule the world and not-not the apes?

105
00:08:17.005 --> 00:08:18.006
I don't know.

106
00:08:18.090 --> 00:08:19.341
Opposable thumb.

107
00:08:21.009 --> 00:08:22.136
Better motor control.

108
00:08:22.719 --> 00:08:24.888
- Bigger brain. Less hair.
- Okay.

109
00:08:24.972 --> 00:08:27.433
Let's try this. What do you do all day?

110
00:08:27.516 --> 00:08:30.811
Right now? Uh. call up total strangers
and beg them for money.

111
00:08:30.894 --> 00:08:34.397
Exactly. You reach out to people
and you tell them a story.

112
00:08:35.107 --> 00:08:37.651
You take a set of data
and you weave meaning around it.

113
00:08:37.733 --> 00:08:40.945
It's what we do. it's who we are.
We're storytellers. meaning-makers.

114
00:08:41.029 --> 00:08:42.281
It's our only superpower.

115
00:08:42.363 --> 00:08:43.866
You. me. Charlotte.

116
00:08:43.949 --> 00:08:46.869
we're really just a collection of stories
we've told ourselves.

117
00:08:46.952 --> 00:08:48.996
Memory is our internal biography.

118
00:08:49.079 --> 00:08:52.833
Information that we've hopped up
with meaning to tell us who we are.

119
00:08:54.126 --> 00:08:57.129
The medication has
erased the book of Charlotte.

120
00:08:58.297 --> 00:09:00.132
Okay? Like I said.

121
00:09:00.215 --> 00:09:02.926
we'll stop the meds. and memory by memory.

122
00:09:03.010 --> 00:09:05.429
you'll fill it back up
again with her story.

123
00:09:05.512 --> 00:09:06.722
Memory by memory?

124
00:09:06.805 --> 00:09:07.806
Memory by memory.

125
00:09:07.890 --> 00:09:09.099
Loving sister.

126
00:09:09.850 --> 00:09:11.518
brilliant naval aviator.

127
00:09:12.019 --> 00:09:14.855
Even the mission to Iran.
but this time you have a choice.

128
00:09:14.938 --> 00:09:18.734
Daniel. you have a choice not to
cripple her with the whole truth.

129
00:09:18.817 --> 00:09:21.236
The trauma of what happened
to her squadron.

130
00:09:21.320 --> 00:09:22.905
You have a choice to leave that behind.

131
00:09:32.623 --> 00:09:33.916
Could I tell her a lie?

132
00:09:34.708 --> 00:09:35.709
Would she believe it?

133
00:09:37.294 --> 00:09:38.712
Why would you lie?

134
00:09:38.796 --> 00:09:41.423
Well. she has a few opinions about me
I wouldn't mind her forgetting.

135
00:09:41.507 --> 00:09:42.674
Oh.

136
00:09:42.758 --> 00:09:45.344
[chuckles]

137
00:09:45.427 --> 00:09:48.222
Actually. you-you could implant a lie.

138
00:09:48.305 --> 00:09:51.391
It would take a lot of time
and great effort.

139
00:09:51.475 --> 00:09:54.019
The real memories ignite faster
because they're already there on the page.

140
00:09:54.103 --> 00:09:55.437
she just can't see them.

141
00:09:56.021 --> 00:09:57.064
[sighs]

142
00:10:01.276 --> 00:10:05.030
You'll need artifacts
to bring back the old memories.

143
00:10:05.114 --> 00:10:08.700
You know. objects from her life.
her childhood.

144
00:10:09.535 --> 00:10:13.580
Memory is in the body. not just the brain.

145
00:10:13.664 --> 00:10:14.915
It's. uh…

146
00:10:14.998 --> 00:10:17.376
It's in the smells of the past.
and the-the meaning

147
00:10:17.459 --> 00:10:19.753
that we wrapped around objects
we had when we were kids.

148
00:10:19.837 --> 00:10:23.549
We use them like shortcuts
to ignite the neural pathways.

149
00:10:25.426 --> 00:10:27.302
Our parents died when we were young.

150
00:10:28.846 --> 00:10:30.347
We moved in with our aunt.

151
00:10:30.431 --> 00:10:32.474
There's not a lot of stuff
from our childhood.

152
00:10:33.725 --> 00:10:38.230
I'm sorry. but there's something else
there between the ones and the zeros.

153
00:10:38.313 --> 00:10:41.108
It's-It's not just neurons and axons.
there's something else.

154
00:10:41.191 --> 00:10:44.153
Something mysterious. like…

155
00:10:44.903 --> 00:10:46.029
like a soul.

156
00:10:46.864 --> 00:10:49.700
And it won't be
controlled by me or anyone else.

157
00:10:51.118 --> 00:10:56.790
So. sometimes. maybe 10% of the time.
it does not work.

158
00:10:58.125 --> 00:11:03.046
But she's responding well.
so you have reason to hope.

159
00:11:04.590 --> 00:11:07.134
Okay? Okay.

160
00:11:16.435 --> 00:11:18.479
- [knocking on door]
- [door opens]

161
00:11:19.354 --> 00:11:22.357
Sorry for the interruption. boss…
[sighs] …There's a woman out here.

162
00:11:22.441 --> 00:11:24.151
Filed a regular missing persons' report.

163
00:11:24.234 --> 00:11:25.944
but she won't leave till she sees you.

164
00:11:26.028 --> 00:11:28.906
It's not a regular
missing persons' report.

165
00:11:36.371 --> 00:11:37.790
The missing person's name?

166
00:11:37.873 --> 00:11:39.458
Orla Kent.

167
00:11:40.167 --> 00:11:41.293
She's my sister.

168
00:11:41.794 --> 00:11:43.295
Shadow to the head of Supply?

169
00:11:44.963 --> 00:11:47.841
I saw her yesterday at the Silo Council.

170
00:11:47.925 --> 00:11:49.051
Spoke to her.

171
00:11:51.512 --> 00:11:53.472
- She's missing?
- She comes to me every night

172
00:11:53.555 --> 00:11:54.556
after her shift.

173
00:11:54.640 --> 00:11:57.059
Last night. nothing.

174
00:11:57.142 --> 00:11:59.019
Maybe she went home and crashed.

175
00:11:59.103 --> 00:12:00.521
No. she'd porter a note.

176
00:12:01.146 --> 00:12:02.314
My parents are old.

177
00:12:02.397 --> 00:12:05.150
They worry. That's our deal.

178
00:12:05.234 --> 00:12:06.276
Since we were kids.

179
00:12:06.360 --> 00:12:08.946
No unexplained absences. no room to worry.

180
00:12:10.405 --> 00:12:14.076
Look. I know you're busy
with a whole lot of stuff

181
00:12:14.159 --> 00:12:17.371
that's more important to everyone
else in the Silo. but something's wrong.

182
00:12:18.122 --> 00:12:19.915
I know it in my bones.

183
00:12:22.376 --> 00:12:23.627
I lied to my parents.

184
00:12:24.461 --> 00:12:26.713
I told them
Orla stayed with me last night.

185
00:12:28.173 --> 00:12:30.175
I can't lie to them again today.

186
00:12:33.220 --> 00:12:35.180
Okay. Uh…

187
00:12:36.932 --> 00:12:38.225
Okay.

188
00:12:46.733 --> 00:12:48.026
Thank you.

189
00:12:57.661 --> 00:12:59.830
[music playing on speaker]

190
00:12:59.913 --> 00:13:01.457
It's all very Frankenstein.

191
00:13:02.541 --> 00:13:03.917
[Anna] Crnkovich?

192
00:13:04.001 --> 00:13:05.461
No. uh. me.

193
00:13:05.544 --> 00:13:06.795
He's asking me to…

194
00:13:06.879 --> 00:13:09.756
[stammers] …I don't know.
take a shopping cart into her brain.

195
00:13:09.840 --> 00:13:12.551
pick a whole lot of parts.
rebuild her soul.

196
00:13:14.303 --> 00:13:15.387
Well…

197
00:13:17.598 --> 00:13:21.268
I mean. wh-who are we
if not the sum of our memories. right?

198
00:13:23.562 --> 00:13:24.730
I guess.

199
00:13:25.731 --> 00:13:29.067
Look. I thought I might go
check on her if that's okay.

200
00:13:29.902 --> 00:13:33.155
I never served. so. you know. some candy.
some magazines to a wounded vet

201
00:13:33.238 --> 00:13:34.948
feels like literally the least I could do.

202
00:13:35.032 --> 00:13:36.158
Sure.

203
00:13:40.996 --> 00:13:42.080
Daniel.

204
00:13:43.540 --> 00:13:45.542
- Hey.
- Helen.

205
00:13:46.335 --> 00:13:47.836
- Hi.
- Hi. [chuckles]

206
00:13:47.920 --> 00:13:50.380
Uh. have you met. uh. Anna Thurman?

207
00:13:50.464 --> 00:13:51.757
Helen Drew.

208
00:13:51.840 --> 00:13:53.133
Not officially. um…

209
00:13:53.967 --> 00:13:56.053
Everyone says your mother's talking points
are bulletproof

210
00:13:56.136 --> 00:13:58.097
since she roped you in. so…

211
00:13:58.180 --> 00:14:01.266
Helen and I
accidentally ended up on a date.

212
00:14:01.350 --> 00:14:03.185
Ooh. [chuckles] Not a date.

213
00:14:03.268 --> 00:14:04.269
Um…

214
00:14:04.895 --> 00:14:07.439
Listen. I just went by your office.
I heard about your sister.

215
00:14:07.523 --> 00:14:10.651
- I wanted to say sorry.
- Thanks.

216
00:14:10.734 --> 00:14:12.194
Is she at Walter Reed?

217
00:14:12.277 --> 00:14:15.614
No. they. uh. um… transferred her
to the Heidi Stensen Clinic.

218
00:14:16.240 --> 00:14:17.241
Wow.

219
00:14:17.950 --> 00:14:19.743
Someone must have
pulled some serious strings.

220
00:14:19.827 --> 00:14:23.497
I can't imagine a naval aviator would
have that kind of money tucked away.

221
00:14:23.580 --> 00:14:25.624
Actually.
I think you'll find that Dr. Crnkovich

222
00:14:25.707 --> 00:14:28.961
has been treating combat veterans
free of charge for years now.

223
00:14:29.753 --> 00:14:32.965
Um… [chuckles] Yeah. I guess. Yeah.

224
00:14:33.048 --> 00:14:35.384
His first trial was on prison populations

225
00:14:35.467 --> 00:14:38.929
in countries too indebted
to US aid to say no.

226
00:14:39.012 --> 00:14:41.098
His second was with the DOD
on first year recruits

227
00:14:41.181 --> 00:14:43.475
who don't get a say
in their medical treatment.

228
00:14:43.559 --> 00:14:46.979
And in both cases.
he took a big blackboard eraser

229
00:14:47.062 --> 00:14:48.689
and wiped out their memories.

230
00:14:48.772 --> 00:14:52.568
He let traumatized combat vets
forget the horrors that they saw.

231
00:14:52.651 --> 00:14:55.028
He let career criminals forget
that they were criminals

232
00:14:55.112 --> 00:14:56.738
and become productive members of society.

233
00:14:56.822 --> 00:15:00.200
But he decides what people remember
and what they don't remember.

234
00:15:01.285 --> 00:15:02.286
Doesn't that worry you?

235
00:15:03.704 --> 00:15:07.082
Well. it's a little more complicated
than that.

236
00:15:07.791 --> 00:15:08.792
And she's my sister.

237
00:15:08.876 --> 00:15:12.337
You know. everything since she became
a fighter pilot worries me.

238
00:15:12.838 --> 00:15:16.467
Is it too cynical to say that he is
using injured vets to test his theories?

239
00:15:16.550 --> 00:15:18.469
- Helen.
- Victor lost his wife

240
00:15:18.552 --> 00:15:21.221
and child in a car accident
when he fell asleep at the wheel.

241
00:15:23.015 --> 00:15:25.225
My guess is he's got more skin
in the trauma game than most.

242
00:15:27.478 --> 00:15:28.479
Hmm.

243
00:15:30.731 --> 00:15:31.732
Take care.

244
00:15:31.815 --> 00:15:34.526
And. uh. send Charlotte my best.

245
00:15:34.610 --> 00:15:35.611
Sure.

246
00:15:42.034 --> 00:15:44.870
You met with a reporter
and you thought it was a date?

247
00:15:46.580 --> 00:15:49.374
Politicians and reporters.
you know it's transact...

248
00:15:49.458 --> 00:15:51.752
It's transactional. yes. I know.

249
00:15:51.835 --> 00:15:53.670
[stammers] I was. uh…

250
00:15:53.754 --> 00:15:55.130
Distracted?

251
00:15:57.007 --> 00:16:01.095
Well. as well as being quite good looking.
she's also good at her job.

252
00:16:01.178 --> 00:16:03.597
Even if the only one she could get
was a shitty one.

253
00:16:03.680 --> 00:16:05.849
- Is she not at the Post?
- Mm-mmm.

254
00:16:05.933 --> 00:16:07.684
No. she hasn't been there for a year.

255
00:16:08.185 --> 00:16:09.478
She was a bad girl.

256
00:16:10.104 --> 00:16:13.482
She's at some online sleaze factory now.

257
00:16:14.316 --> 00:16:16.902
Still. she's a reporter.

258
00:16:16.985 --> 00:16:18.570
She got what she wanted
and you got nothing.

259
00:16:19.613 --> 00:16:20.614
What'd she get?

260
00:16:21.782 --> 00:16:23.867
You told her where
Charlotte's being treated.

261
00:16:25.953 --> 00:16:27.454
And you told her for free.

262
00:16:38.549 --> 00:16:39.550
[clicks tongue]

263
00:16:52.646 --> 00:16:54.314
She said you should take the whole box…

264
00:16:55.315 --> 00:16:56.316
for luck.

265
00:16:58.068 --> 00:16:59.486
Okay?

266
00:17:01.405 --> 00:17:03.157
[Martha] "You wanted the truth.

267
00:17:03.240 --> 00:17:05.367
The truth is I love you.

268
00:17:06.284 --> 00:17:10.456
Have no fear. they're good in Supply."

269
00:17:16.169 --> 00:17:17.421
Mayor?

270
00:17:18.589 --> 00:17:19.590
Mayor?

271
00:17:20.340 --> 00:17:23.302
Mrs. Sims asked me to log
our movements more formally today.

272
00:17:23.385 --> 00:17:24.511
[tools whirring]

273
00:17:24.595 --> 00:17:25.803
[Shirley] Get back to Supply.

274
00:17:25.888 --> 00:17:29.016
If they don't find us more rebar.
the stairs…

275
00:17:30.100 --> 00:17:32.394
they'll only be ready
for their grandchildren.

276
00:17:35.147 --> 00:17:36.148
Cover me.

277
00:17:45.491 --> 00:17:47.576
You know. you still gotta talk to her.

278
00:17:48.076 --> 00:17:49.077
I can't.

279
00:17:58.962 --> 00:18:00.464
She asked for your help.

280
00:18:05.469 --> 00:18:06.470
I can't.

281
00:18:06.553 --> 00:18:07.554
Okay.

282
00:18:08.097 --> 00:18:09.598
Maybe I should check with someone.

283
00:18:09.681 --> 00:18:12.101
[stammers] It's safe and all
to go down but…

284
00:18:12.601 --> 00:18:14.311
Why? Who would you check with?

285
00:18:14.394 --> 00:18:17.231
I'm the mayor. This is my security.

286
00:18:17.314 --> 00:18:18.565
[Knox] Teddy.

287
00:18:19.483 --> 00:18:20.859
What's going on?

288
00:18:20.943 --> 00:18:23.904
Uh. the mayor wants to go down.

289
00:18:24.905 --> 00:18:26.156
Oh.

290
00:18:26.865 --> 00:18:28.784
Madam Mayor.
can I ask why you want to go down?

291
00:18:29.952 --> 00:18:31.495
Do I have to give you a reason?

292
00:18:31.995 --> 00:18:35.124
Well. I'm in charge
of rebuilding the stairs

293
00:18:35.207 --> 00:18:37.251
and no one gets on a rope
without my say-so.

294
00:18:41.713 --> 00:18:45.926
Um. you know I don't really remember you?

295
00:18:46.009 --> 00:18:47.094
Yeah. I know.

296
00:18:47.845 --> 00:18:50.931
And I have this feeling
we didn't really see eye to eye.

297
00:18:51.598 --> 00:18:52.808
We did all right.

298
00:18:55.060 --> 00:18:58.230
- Uh. I wanna talk to Martha Walker.
- Oh.

299
00:18:58.313 --> 00:19:01.275
Well. you're in luck. She went up to 60
to get some medical supplies.

300
00:19:02.151 --> 00:19:03.861
She should be back down any second.

301
00:19:05.821 --> 00:19:06.822
Right.

302
00:19:07.698 --> 00:19:09.700
Well. we. um… we'll wait.

303
00:19:11.368 --> 00:19:13.412
Uh. Madam Mayor.

304
00:19:14.538 --> 00:19:16.415
while you wait.
can I talk to you for a second?

305
00:19:17.666 --> 00:19:18.667
In private.

306
00:19:19.418 --> 00:19:20.919
Yeah. Sure.

307
00:19:23.881 --> 00:19:24.882
It's okay.

308
00:19:28.802 --> 00:19:31.430
I. uh… Shit. [chuckles]

309
00:19:32.806 --> 00:19:36.769
Camille gave us all instructions
about how to talk to you

310
00:19:36.852 --> 00:19:38.145
so I don't fuck up your recovery.

311
00:19:38.228 --> 00:19:39.938
Oh. it's okay. Go ahead.

312
00:19:43.692 --> 00:19:45.694
You asked Shirley about Bernard Holland.

313
00:19:46.361 --> 00:19:47.362
Yeah?

314
00:19:47.446 --> 00:19:49.072
This morning she remembered something.

315
00:19:49.865 --> 00:19:54.453
I don't know if this is helpful.
but during the rebellion… [sighs]

316
00:19:55.204 --> 00:19:56.538
…a guy came down.

317
00:19:57.581 --> 00:19:59.041
He said he was Bernard's shadow.

318
00:20:00.417 --> 00:20:03.545
Well. we didn't have time for him.
Shirl was just gonna throw him in a cell.

319
00:20:03.629 --> 00:20:05.255
but he said he knew you.

320
00:20:06.381 --> 00:20:08.342
He said that when you went over that hill.

321
00:20:08.425 --> 00:20:10.719
someone had seen you go inside somewhere

322
00:20:10.803 --> 00:20:13.555
and that maybe you were still alive.

323
00:20:14.223 --> 00:20:16.141
- Did he say who?
- No.

324
00:20:17.226 --> 00:20:19.478
All I know is Shirl took him down
to the digger void.

325
00:20:20.521 --> 00:20:22.022
He was looking for something
at the bottom.

326
00:20:22.106 --> 00:20:23.482
He wouldn't say what it was.

327
00:20:23.565 --> 00:20:25.776
But if this guy really was
Bernard's shadow.

328
00:20:26.985 --> 00:20:28.153
maybe he could help you.

329
00:20:29.571 --> 00:20:30.989
[stammers] What's his name?

330
00:20:32.157 --> 00:20:33.534
Lukas Kyle.

331
00:20:38.705 --> 00:20:42.167
[sighs] I'm getting an assistant
in my next life.

332
00:20:42.251 --> 00:20:46.630
I am so done with doing things for someone
who should be doing them himself.

333
00:20:46.713 --> 00:20:48.715
Hi. Let me start over.

334
00:20:48.799 --> 00:20:51.301
I'm with Congressman
Daniel Keene's office.

335
00:20:51.385 --> 00:20:53.429
He asked me to stop by.
check on his sister.

336
00:20:53.512 --> 00:20:55.264
Maybe. um… [smacks lips]

337
00:20:55.347 --> 00:20:57.099
…maybe get her outside?

338
00:20:59.184 --> 00:21:01.311
Why didn't Shirley tell me herself?

339
00:21:05.274 --> 00:21:06.400
I think…

340
00:21:08.152 --> 00:21:09.278
[sighs]

341
00:21:10.779 --> 00:21:13.490
We're all struggling
with how to wrap our heads around

342
00:21:13.574 --> 00:21:15.742
what you remember and what you don't.

343
00:21:15.826 --> 00:21:16.869
[grunts]

344
00:21:16.952 --> 00:21:20.164
[chuckles] And I know… I know
that you won't remember this.

345
00:21:21.665 --> 00:21:25.169
but Shirley.
she armors up when she's hurting.

346
00:21:28.797 --> 00:21:31.300
I mean. when you first came back.

347
00:21:32.718 --> 00:21:36.847
Shirl camped outside your hospital room
for ten days straight.

348
00:21:36.930 --> 00:21:38.182
Wouldn't leave your side.

349
00:21:39.057 --> 00:21:42.144
I practically had to carry her
back down to Mechanical.

350
00:21:44.021 --> 00:21:47.858
Then the rumors started that you had lost
a lot of your memory in the fire.

351
00:21:47.941 --> 00:21:49.985
but Shirl wouldn't have it.

352
00:21:50.068 --> 00:21:51.487
You wouldn't forget her.

353
00:21:52.070 --> 00:21:57.326
She ran up 144 levels to be there
your first time out in the cafeteria.

354
00:21:57.409 --> 00:21:58.702
Waited in the back.

355
00:21:59.203 --> 00:22:01.497
Let everybody else get their piece of you.

356
00:22:03.081 --> 00:22:06.168
And then when it was her turn.
you looked straight through her.

357
00:22:09.338 --> 00:22:10.339
I…

358
00:22:12.132 --> 00:22:17.012
I just think talking to you
hurts a little too much right now.

359
00:22:21.517 --> 00:22:22.643
Here's Walker.

360
00:22:26.772 --> 00:22:30.359
Madam Mayor. this is Martha Walker.

361
00:22:31.151 --> 00:22:32.277
Don't bother.

362
00:22:32.361 --> 00:22:34.571
She has no idea who I am.

363
00:22:34.655 --> 00:22:35.989
Do you?

364
00:22:38.200 --> 00:22:39.409
Let's start with something simple.

365
00:22:39.493 --> 00:22:40.828
You still drink coffee?

366
00:22:40.911 --> 00:22:45.040
Or am I not allowed to ask that
'cause you're too fragile?

367
00:22:46.166 --> 00:22:47.251
I drink coffee.

368
00:22:49.670 --> 00:22:50.754
Good.

369
00:22:55.968 --> 00:22:57.719
So what have they been telling you?

370
00:22:57.803 --> 00:23:00.097
[huffs] Well. they said that I used to

371
00:23:00.180 --> 00:23:02.724
- spend a lot of time in your workshop.
- [resident 1] The mayor's coming.

372
00:23:02.808 --> 00:23:04.768
[resident 2] Madam Mayor. go ahead.

373
00:23:04.852 --> 00:23:06.979
She can wait like the rest of us.

374
00:23:11.567 --> 00:23:12.568
So…

375
00:23:13.235 --> 00:23:18.198
I know that my main responsibility
was the generator. right?

376
00:23:19.283 --> 00:23:22.077
But I wanna know why…
why did I spend so much time with you?

377
00:23:23.579 --> 00:23:25.330
You came for advice.

378
00:23:25.414 --> 00:23:26.665
Which you never took.

379
00:23:27.624 --> 00:23:28.667
Why?

380
00:23:29.460 --> 00:23:31.211
- Hi.
- Pigheadedness. arrogance.

381
00:23:31.295 --> 00:23:33.755
Hey. two black coffees.

382
00:23:33.839 --> 00:23:34.840
Hold the fawning.

383
00:23:38.886 --> 00:23:40.596
So why'd you wanna see me?

384
00:23:43.265 --> 00:23:45.267
I got a note last night.

385
00:23:46.685 --> 00:23:48.103
Did you send it?

386
00:23:48.187 --> 00:23:49.313
Wasn't me.

387
00:23:49.396 --> 00:23:50.647
What did it say?

388
00:23:51.774 --> 00:23:52.858
Oh.

389
00:23:52.941 --> 00:23:54.234
You don't trust me.

390
00:23:55.694 --> 00:23:56.862
I want to trust you.

391
00:23:56.945 --> 00:23:58.322
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

392
00:23:58.405 --> 00:24:00.115
W-Why would that be?

393
00:24:03.285 --> 00:24:05.871
I remember you sent me a note
the day that I went out to clean.

394
00:24:08.665 --> 00:24:10.209
[whispering] "They're good in Supply."

395
00:24:10.751 --> 00:24:13.128
Which showed me that
you had swapped the heat tape.

396
00:24:13.712 --> 00:24:15.964
Something that you could've
been sent out to clean for.

397
00:24:17.925 --> 00:24:21.053
And you wouldn't do that to anyone.
you would do that to someone that you…

398
00:24:23.430 --> 00:24:25.015
Yeah. well. that was then.

399
00:24:26.391 --> 00:24:29.728
So what? You don't remember something.
poof. it's gone.

400
00:24:30.813 --> 00:24:32.606
Might just as well not have existed.

401
00:24:35.109 --> 00:24:36.110
Okay.

402
00:24:38.278 --> 00:24:39.279
Well…

403
00:24:41.949 --> 00:24:43.200
The note I got said.

404
00:24:43.992 --> 00:24:47.371
"If you want to know the truth.
go to the marketplace at 2:00."

405
00:24:48.455 --> 00:24:50.791
So I wanna know.
do I go to the marketplace?

406
00:24:51.416 --> 00:24:52.793
Do I go… [stammers]

407
00:24:53.544 --> 00:24:54.545
[sighs]

408
00:24:56.088 --> 00:24:58.924
You know what was
the most irritating thing about you?

409
00:25:00.342 --> 00:25:04.346
If there was a problem.
a question. a decision to be made

410
00:25:04.430 --> 00:25:06.974
and everyone was pointing
in one direction.

411
00:25:07.057 --> 00:25:10.477
you would decide that the only direction
to go in was the opposite.

412
00:25:10.561 --> 00:25:12.855
Right. Okay. That's quite irritating.

413
00:25:12.938 --> 00:25:16.859
No. What was irritating
was that 99% of the time you were right.

414
00:25:18.694 --> 00:25:20.612
Because you trusted your gut.

415
00:25:22.906 --> 00:25:25.742
So my question to you now is.
what does your gut say?

416
00:25:32.040 --> 00:25:33.459
I can't.

417
00:25:33.542 --> 00:25:38.130
[smacks lips] You see. the person I risked
my life for. she was a fighter.

418
00:25:38.213 --> 00:25:41.425
She would have fought
with every inch of stubbornness.

419
00:25:41.508 --> 00:25:43.927
arrogance. pigheadedness in her body.

420
00:25:49.641 --> 00:25:51.894
[stammers] That's it?

421
00:25:59.276 --> 00:26:01.236
- What's that?
- Are you even trying?

422
00:26:02.070 --> 00:26:03.155
To remember?

423
00:26:04.823 --> 00:26:08.327
What do you m… I'm here. Right?
So. yeah. What…

424
00:26:09.953 --> 00:26:11.079
I get…

425
00:26:12.372 --> 00:26:16.627
I get splinters of memory. or something.
I don't know what it is.

426
00:26:16.710 --> 00:26:21.715
And the-the more I try and hold onto it.
it just slips away so…

427
00:26:22.716 --> 00:26:23.759
I don't know what to do.

428
00:26:25.636 --> 00:26:26.637
Try harder.

429
00:26:36.438 --> 00:26:37.731
I don't remember you.

430
00:26:38.941 --> 00:26:42.194
Ah. that's okay.
I'm not taking it personally.

431
00:26:43.445 --> 00:26:44.905
You're the only one.

432
00:26:44.988 --> 00:26:46.281
How about we go sit over there?

433
00:26:46.907 --> 00:26:51.245
It's so good to get away
from the constant staring. and questions…

434
00:26:53.080 --> 00:26:57.167
and pressure to vomit up
something of value.

435
00:26:58.836 --> 00:27:04.258
You have any military visitors yet.
hoping you'll vomit up something of value?

436
00:27:05.384 --> 00:27:06.468
Not yet.

437
00:27:08.846 --> 00:27:13.058
Mostly… [sighs]
…my brother hovering over me.

438
00:27:13.642 --> 00:27:16.395
sweating bullets
that I'll remember something.

439
00:27:16.478 --> 00:27:18.480
- Yeah.
- Remember him.

440
00:27:19.690 --> 00:27:23.444
Well. for the record. I'm a reporter.

441
00:27:24.820 --> 00:27:26.572
I want you to vomit up something too.

442
00:27:29.700 --> 00:27:30.951
We met a couple of times.

443
00:27:31.452 --> 00:27:33.745
Something was bothering you
about the mission to Iran.

444
00:27:33.829 --> 00:27:35.622
I don't remember anything
about the mission.

445
00:27:35.706 --> 00:27:39.042
Part of what I do is help people
get their stories straight. okay?

446
00:27:39.126 --> 00:27:40.627
I help them fill in the blanks.

447
00:27:40.711 --> 00:27:44.631
So I thought I could tell you what I know
about the mission

448
00:27:44.715 --> 00:27:47.384
and what they're saying officially.

449
00:27:47.468 --> 00:27:49.720
Maybe that'll help stir something up.

450
00:28:00.022 --> 00:28:01.774
[Charlotte panting]

451
00:28:01.857 --> 00:28:02.858
Charlotte.

452
00:28:02.941 --> 00:28:05.486
[thunder rumbling]

453
00:28:05.569 --> 00:28:06.570
[distorted] Charlotte?

454
00:28:07.654 --> 00:28:10.657
- Hey. Hey. Are you okay? Hey.
- [panting. breathes shakily]

455
00:28:12.993 --> 00:28:14.745
[breathing shakily]

456
00:28:32.054 --> 00:28:33.305
- Are you okay?
- Yeah.

457
00:28:39.144 --> 00:28:42.523
All right. excuse me. Hey.
excuse me. guys. Thank you. Excuse me.

458
00:28:45.067 --> 00:28:46.527
[people chattering]

459
00:28:59.748 --> 00:29:02.960
Look. I. uh… I know
this is not a part of your orders.

460
00:29:03.043 --> 00:29:04.586
- but I-I need some space.
- Mm-hmm.

461
00:29:04.670 --> 00:29:07.840
So. um. could you give me 30 minutes or…

462
00:29:07.923 --> 00:29:09.550
Have you met Mrs. Sims?

463
00:29:10.134 --> 00:29:13.095
I let you outta my sight. then she'll use
my intestines for dental floss...

464
00:29:13.178 --> 00:29:14.680
- I know. but I need to...
- Juliette.

465
00:29:15.180 --> 00:29:16.974
- It's her. It's Juliette.
- [Jerry] Hi. guys.

466
00:29:17.057 --> 00:29:19.309
- Wait. wait. Don't.
- Hey. whoa. whoa. whoa. whoa. whoa.

467
00:29:19.393 --> 00:29:21.979
- All right. guys. Sorry. no.
- [Juliette] Jerry. Hey. No. no. no.

468
00:29:22.062 --> 00:29:23.522
Just give the mayor some space. okay?

469
00:29:23.605 --> 00:29:25.149
- Back up.
- What the fuck are you…

470
00:29:25.232 --> 00:29:26.900
- Did you touch me?
- What are you talking about?

471
00:29:26.984 --> 00:29:28.277
- He fucking touched me!
- [clamoring]

472
00:29:28.360 --> 00:29:29.570
- I'm sorry.
- Hey!

473
00:29:29.653 --> 00:29:32.156
[all clamoring]

474
00:29:32.239 --> 00:29:34.783
- I'm sorry.
- You need to take your hands off her.

475
00:29:34.867 --> 00:29:37.911
Madam Mayor. This is a misunderstanding.

476
00:29:39.329 --> 00:29:41.540
[shouting. grunting]

477
00:30:00.976 --> 00:30:02.478
Ma'am. Are you lost?

478
00:30:03.812 --> 00:30:06.482
If you want the truth. come with me.

479
00:30:09.860 --> 00:30:10.986
[sighs]

480
00:30:12.905 --> 00:30:13.906
[pants]

481
00:30:13.989 --> 00:30:15.741
Match me. Three…

482
00:30:15.824 --> 00:30:17.826
[exhales. inhales deeply]

483
00:30:17.910 --> 00:30:19.703
That's it. [blows]

484
00:30:19.787 --> 00:30:22.539
- [breathes deeply]
- That's it. Match my breathing.

485
00:30:22.623 --> 00:30:24.833
- In for three seconds and hold.
- [pants] Okay.

486
00:30:26.084 --> 00:30:28.212
And out. [exhales deeply]

487
00:30:28.295 --> 00:30:30.506
Good. You're doing good. Easy now.

488
00:30:30.589 --> 00:30:33.175
- Let it go. Okay. Good.
- [breathes deeply]

489
00:30:34.468 --> 00:30:35.803
[Victor] Charlotte seemed to know her.

490
00:30:35.886 --> 00:30:38.097
- Did you call the police?
- No. I was waiting for you.

491
00:30:58.742 --> 00:31:00.577
[keys rattle]

492
00:31:08.544 --> 00:31:10.129
- Who… Who are you?
- [keys rattling]

493
00:31:10.212 --> 00:31:13.215
- [lock clicks]
- [chuckles]

494
00:31:13.298 --> 00:31:14.508
What?

495
00:31:14.591 --> 00:31:15.592
[chuckles]

496
00:31:17.219 --> 00:31:21.723
Um… I-I'm the man you strong-armed
into helping you with the hard drive.

497
00:31:21.807 --> 00:31:23.308
- What?
- Uh…

498
00:31:23.392 --> 00:31:25.936
Patrick Kennedy. whose life's
never sucked more than when I met you.

499
00:31:26.019 --> 00:31:27.312
You're one of the fugitives.

500
00:31:27.396 --> 00:31:29.857
Uh. Danny. You screwed my life too.

501
00:31:29.940 --> 00:31:33.277
Landed me in Judicial seclusion.
Trying to forget it. probably never will.

502
00:31:33.861 --> 00:31:36.613
Sandy. I worked for you
when you were sheriff.

503
00:31:36.697 --> 00:31:39.408
You didn't screw up my life
but. uh. I still don't like you.

504
00:31:40.117 --> 00:31:42.119
Okay. and you… [stammers]
You sent me the note?

505
00:31:42.202 --> 00:31:44.830
[stammers] Well. I didn't. She did.
She wrote it. I don't know why she wrote

506
00:31:44.913 --> 00:31:46.915
- the whole thing about the truth.
- You sent me the note?

507
00:31:46.999 --> 00:31:48.417
- 'Cause I wanted her to show up.
- Yeah.

508
00:31:48.500 --> 00:31:49.877
Okay. but what you should have said is.

509
00:31:49.960 --> 00:31:52.212
- "Why are you lying about the outside?"
- [Sandy] Yeah.

510
00:31:52.754 --> 00:31:54.590
Well. I'm-I'm not lying. What do you mean?

511
00:31:54.673 --> 00:31:57.843
The Jane Carmody video. I saw you see it.

512
00:31:57.926 --> 00:32:00.012
- [stammers]
- The flowers. And the trees.

513
00:32:00.095 --> 00:32:01.847
- And the birds.
- And the birds.

514
00:32:02.431 --> 00:32:04.391
And then you went outside
and you came back…

515
00:32:04.475 --> 00:32:05.851
- [grunts]
- …right?

516
00:32:05.934 --> 00:32:07.811
So why are you saying that it's not safe?

517
00:32:07.895 --> 00:32:11.106
It's not safe 'cause it's not safe.

518
00:32:11.190 --> 00:32:14.902
When you went over the hill.
what did you see?

519
00:32:14.985 --> 00:32:16.904
I've seen what… what we've all seen.

520
00:32:16.987 --> 00:32:17.988
I've seen the… [stammers]

521
00:32:18.071 --> 00:32:21.366
I walk over the hill
and then I walk into a refuge hut. right?

522
00:32:21.450 --> 00:32:22.826
But do you remember that?

523
00:32:22.910 --> 00:32:23.994
- Really?
- Huh?

524
00:32:24.495 --> 00:32:27.080
Or are you just remembering
what you've been shown?

525
00:32:31.293 --> 00:32:32.503
No. I…

526
00:32:35.172 --> 00:32:36.924
I… Okay. I don't…

527
00:32:38.091 --> 00:32:39.551
I don't. I don't know. I don't know.

528
00:32:40.135 --> 00:32:41.428
I don't know. I don't know.

529
00:32:42.179 --> 00:32:45.140
Then… [stammers] …maybe they did it.
Maybe… Maybe they actually did it.

530
00:32:45.224 --> 00:32:46.809
- What?
- [stammers] Hold on one second.

531
00:32:46.892 --> 00:32:49.603
You remember the. um…
the drugs that Sims offered me?

532
00:32:49.686 --> 00:32:52.272
"Swallow these pills and you'll forget
that we led your wife to her grave"?

533
00:32:52.356 --> 00:32:53.982
Do you remember that?
I said it was total bullshit.

534
00:32:54.066 --> 00:32:55.150
- Hey.
- Maybe it's not bullshit.

535
00:32:55.234 --> 00:32:57.236
- I'm sorry. All I'm saying is…
- Just…

536
00:32:58.278 --> 00:33:01.406
What if your head injury
is not because of the fire?

537
00:33:02.366 --> 00:33:03.367
Let me ask you something.

538
00:33:03.450 --> 00:33:05.661
Are-Are you receiving
a lot of medical attention right now?

539
00:33:05.744 --> 00:33:07.204
- Yeah.
- Yeah. like being asked to swallow

540
00:33:07.287 --> 00:33:08.455
a whole bunch of pills?

541
00:33:10.207 --> 00:33:11.416
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

542
00:33:13.585 --> 00:33:15.629
[smacks lips] Wake the fuck up. people.
I'm sorry.

543
00:33:15.712 --> 00:33:20.717
But you are the only one
who has ever gone out and survived.

544
00:33:20.801 --> 00:33:24.221
And now. surprise. sur-fucking-prise.

545
00:33:24.304 --> 00:33:26.432
She doesn't remember anything
except what they tell her.

546
00:33:29.309 --> 00:33:30.644
Get the helmets.

547
00:33:31.520 --> 00:33:32.896
[sighs. mutters]

548
00:33:35.274 --> 00:33:36.275
[sighs]

549
00:33:39.111 --> 00:33:42.030
Hey. Hey. What the fuck were you doing?

550
00:33:42.865 --> 00:33:44.241
What she wanted.

551
00:33:44.324 --> 00:33:46.201
- [scoffs]
- Our non-date?

552
00:33:46.285 --> 00:33:48.871
- Wasn't randomly fishing for information.
- Oh. I know.

553
00:33:48.954 --> 00:33:51.290
You went to Charlotte for a story.
and then when you didn't get it.

554
00:33:51.373 --> 00:33:53.792
- you came to me.
- No. you idiot. I didn't go to her.

555
00:33:54.751 --> 00:33:56.003
She came to me.

556
00:33:56.587 --> 00:33:57.588
[sighs]

557
00:33:58.630 --> 00:33:59.631
She read my stuff.

558
00:34:00.132 --> 00:34:02.217
She thought she could trust me
and we met in secret.

559
00:34:03.677 --> 00:34:07.139
There were questions that she wanted
to ask. questions that she couldn't ask.

560
00:34:07.222 --> 00:34:09.682
The best she could do
was point me in the right direction.

561
00:34:16.064 --> 00:34:17.356
Right direction for what?

562
00:34:18.484 --> 00:34:20.736
She thought something was off
about the mission to Iran.

563
00:34:21.737 --> 00:34:24.740
She thought you might be willing to use
what little congressional power you've got

564
00:34:24.823 --> 00:34:26.240
to try and find some answers.

565
00:34:28.075 --> 00:34:29.244
What kind of questions?

566
00:34:30.662 --> 00:34:33.749
The kind that an administration
with a hard-on for going to war with Iran

567
00:34:33.832 --> 00:34:34.874
don't want asked.

568
00:34:35.374 --> 00:34:38.003
Like. "Was the dirty bomb attack
on D.C. even real?"

569
00:34:41.798 --> 00:34:45.427
She told me not all missions planned
for Iran were related to the nukes.

570
00:34:46.135 --> 00:34:49.055
The one she was on. going to the mountains
up next to Turkmenistan.

571
00:34:49.139 --> 00:34:51.809
their planes were going to be loaded
with bunker busters.

572
00:34:52.726 --> 00:34:54.937
She said they-they pulled out
the comms units

573
00:34:55.019 --> 00:34:57.106
and installed this old school system
from the '80s.

574
00:34:57.189 --> 00:34:58.440
Why would they do that?

575
00:34:59.358 --> 00:35:01.026
What do old comms give you? [sighs]

576
00:35:01.110 --> 00:35:03.904
[stammers] You don't want
your email hacked? You use a typewriter.

577
00:35:03.987 --> 00:35:06.782
Don't want your planes hacked? You take
them out of the digital playing field.

578
00:35:06.865 --> 00:35:09.159
She said.
"Might as well be flying Tomcats."

579
00:35:11.495 --> 00:35:13.205
Everyone else
in Charlotte's squadron is dead.

580
00:35:13.288 --> 00:35:15.415
and she scores a magical transfer here?

581
00:35:16.208 --> 00:35:17.584
Where her treatment will what?

582
00:35:18.210 --> 00:35:19.878
Make sure she never remembers
what happened?

583
00:35:22.923 --> 00:35:25.634
I didn't sneak in there today
to get some story.

584
00:35:27.010 --> 00:35:28.429
Your sister wanted the truth.

585
00:35:29.847 --> 00:35:32.891
Badly enough to risk her career
and risk going to jail for it.

586
00:35:34.226 --> 00:35:35.227
I think she still does.

587
00:35:36.395 --> 00:35:40.983
Which just leaves the question.
was she right to send me to you for help?

588
00:35:44.403 --> 00:35:46.822
And then a raider came up behind her.

589
00:35:48.282 --> 00:35:53.120
They talked for a few seconds
and then Juliette followed the raider.

590
00:35:54.746 --> 00:35:56.957
Down an alley
and into one of the storage rooms.

591
00:36:00.169 --> 00:36:01.628
Which storage room?

592
00:36:06.467 --> 00:36:07.676
I can show you…

593
00:36:09.803 --> 00:36:11.305
but there's something I want in return.

594
00:36:12.014 --> 00:36:13.640
And what might that be?

595
00:36:19.646 --> 00:36:22.733
This one we grabbed from IT the other day.

596
00:36:23.233 --> 00:36:24.902
Printed inside is the number 18.

597
00:36:25.903 --> 00:36:27.446
Same number as on the hard drive.

598
00:36:28.655 --> 00:36:31.366
But this one. the helmet you wore back?

599
00:36:32.951 --> 00:36:34.077
It says 17.

600
00:36:51.261 --> 00:36:52.262
[Sandy] Juliette.

601
00:36:53.597 --> 00:36:54.598
You had a sign.

602
00:36:55.432 --> 00:37:00.729
You held it up to the camera
and it said. "Not safe. Do not come out."

603
00:37:04.650 --> 00:37:06.276
I worked for you.

604
00:37:07.027 --> 00:37:09.029
I know your handwriting.
You didn't write it.

605
00:37:10.489 --> 00:37:11.740
Who wrote the sign?

606
00:37:11.824 --> 00:37:14.618
I don't know. I don't know.
I don't know… It's fucking gone.

607
00:37:27.464 --> 00:37:28.632
[whistles]

608
00:37:30.259 --> 00:37:31.760
[whistles]

609
00:37:34.096 --> 00:37:35.389
Great. What now?

610
00:37:36.098 --> 00:37:37.975
We get back to looking for Lukas Kyle.

611
00:37:38.058 --> 00:37:39.476
Ninety-two days without a sighting.

612
00:37:39.560 --> 00:37:41.353
But you know what they say.
93rd day's a charm.

613
00:37:41.437 --> 00:37:43.021
Hey. Hey. wait. Lukas Kyle?

614
00:37:43.105 --> 00:37:45.274
- [Sandy] Yeah. he was Bernard's shadow.
- No. I know. I know.

615
00:37:45.357 --> 00:37:46.442
Why are you looking for him?

616
00:37:46.525 --> 00:37:49.278
Because before he became Bernard's shadow.
he was in the mines.

617
00:37:49.361 --> 00:37:50.362
Why?

618
00:37:50.446 --> 00:37:53.740
Because you showed him
a red-level relic and he didn't report it.

619
00:37:54.241 --> 00:37:55.951
I figured you showed him that hard drive.

620
00:37:56.034 --> 00:37:57.035
I don't…

621
00:37:58.745 --> 00:38:00.205
I don't remember giving him…

622
00:38:00.289 --> 00:38:02.541
[stammers] I know.
You don't remember anything. I got it.

623
00:38:02.624 --> 00:38:03.625
Wa-wa-wait. Stop.

624
00:38:03.709 --> 00:38:07.296
So Lukas is sent to the mines.
but why then did Bernard pull him out?

625
00:38:07.379 --> 00:38:08.589
Why? I don't get it.

626
00:38:08.672 --> 00:38:10.424
That's what we're trying to find out.

627
00:38:10.507 --> 00:38:12.468
But he hasn't been seen
since the rebellion.

628
00:38:12.551 --> 00:38:13.927
[whistles in distance]

629
00:38:14.011 --> 00:38:16.138
Fuck. Get her out of here. Go. go. go. go.

630
00:38:16.221 --> 00:38:17.431
- You gotta go. Now.
- We gotta go.

631
00:38:17.514 --> 00:38:18.515
- Now.
- Hey. Okay.

632
00:38:24.146 --> 00:38:26.356
Madam Mayor. step aside please.

633
00:38:28.525 --> 00:38:29.985
- Bring in the ram.
- Are you all right?

634
00:38:30.068 --> 00:38:31.069
- Yeah.
- Hold on.

635
00:38:31.862 --> 00:38:33.405
Clear the mayor! Get her out.

636
00:38:35.574 --> 00:38:36.825
[Emerson] Now!

637
00:38:36.909 --> 00:38:37.993
[grunts]

638
00:38:45.709 --> 00:38:46.710
[sighs]

639
00:39:21.829 --> 00:39:22.996
What did Kennedy want?

640
00:39:24.289 --> 00:39:26.708
He just kept on going on
about it being safe outside.

641
00:39:26.792 --> 00:39:29.336
that I was lying
and I need to tell the truth.

642
00:39:29.419 --> 00:39:32.297
- But you know the truth.
- Yeah. I do.

643
00:39:36.427 --> 00:39:39.138
When you had the dream about Bernard.

644
00:39:39.221 --> 00:39:43.392
you said there was something
you had to do but couldn't remember what.

645
00:39:43.475 --> 00:39:44.476
Yeah?

646
00:39:45.018 --> 00:39:46.937
Did Kennedy say anything about that?

647
00:39:47.020 --> 00:39:48.021
What? No.

648
00:39:48.856 --> 00:39:53.193
No. he just kept yelling that I need
to tell everyone that it's good outside.

649
00:39:54.153 --> 00:39:55.529
- That's all he said?
- Yeah.

650
00:39:56.029 --> 00:39:57.030
Okay.

651
00:39:59.324 --> 00:40:02.453
Look. you get that because of that note.

652
00:40:02.536 --> 00:40:05.372
you walked blindly into something
that could've gone very wrong?

653
00:40:05.456 --> 00:40:09.042
- Yeah. [clears throat]
- This is why I have Jerry on you. Okay?

654
00:40:09.126 --> 00:40:10.627
Because the only way I can keep you safe

655
00:40:10.711 --> 00:40:12.171
- is if we're in it together.
- Okay.

656
00:40:13.005 --> 00:40:14.465
There can't be secrets.

657
00:40:16.008 --> 00:40:19.636
I know. And I didn't think it through
and I'm sorry.

658
00:40:19.720 --> 00:40:21.346
I should… I shouldn't have. I know.

659
00:40:22.222 --> 00:40:23.974
- I know.
- Okay.

660
00:40:24.057 --> 00:40:25.392
- Okay?
- Yeah.

661
00:40:25.476 --> 00:40:28.771
- Yeah. Are we good?
- Not quite. I. um…

662
00:40:28.854 --> 00:40:30.230
I need you to meet someone.

663
00:40:32.691 --> 00:40:33.984
Why?

664
00:40:34.067 --> 00:40:36.737
She followed you. [sighs] She…

665
00:40:36.820 --> 00:40:39.323
The only way she'd tell us where you were
is if she could talk to you.

666
00:40:39.406 --> 00:40:41.909
- I said she could have one minute.
- Are you kidding me? I'm tired.

667
00:40:41.992 --> 00:40:43.327
- It's a minute.
- [sighs]

668
00:40:43.911 --> 00:40:45.829
- Okay. Yep. Mm-hmm.
- Yeah?

669
00:40:51.502 --> 00:40:53.337
This is. um…

670
00:40:53.420 --> 00:40:54.713
Juliette.

671
00:40:55.756 --> 00:40:59.051
- Right.
- We call ourselves that. In tribute.

672
00:41:03.430 --> 00:41:04.431
Oh.

673
00:41:05.099 --> 00:41:06.642
Did it hurt getting that?

674
00:41:06.725 --> 00:41:08.310
[chuckles] A bit.

675
00:41:10.187 --> 00:41:11.313
[chuckles] A lot. actually.

676
00:41:11.396 --> 00:41:12.898
You know what it means?

677
00:41:14.900 --> 00:41:16.485
- No.
- [Juliette] No?

678
00:41:16.568 --> 00:41:20.697
We just… We just thought that if you
had it then it must mean something good.

679
00:41:21.198 --> 00:41:22.199
Right.

680
00:41:22.699 --> 00:41:24.618
[fan] Would you tell me what it means?

681
00:41:25.911 --> 00:41:29.331
Sorry. what's your name? What do
your parents… What do they call you?

682
00:41:30.833 --> 00:41:32.334
- Evelyn.
- Evelyn.

683
00:41:32.417 --> 00:41:33.585
Well. that's a good name.

684
00:41:35.212 --> 00:41:36.213
Um…

685
00:41:41.301 --> 00:41:43.011
I don't know what it means.

686
00:41:43.095 --> 00:41:44.471
I don't even remember getting it.

687
00:41:44.555 --> 00:41:48.934
So. I guess you just got marks
on your body that don't mean anything.

688
00:41:51.437 --> 00:41:53.105
But. yeah.

689
00:41:53.689 --> 00:41:54.690
Sorry.

690
00:41:56.024 --> 00:41:58.527
- [Evelyn] Maybe.
- Hmm?

691
00:41:58.610 --> 00:41:59.611
[Evelyn] Maybe not.

692
00:42:00.112 --> 00:42:01.280
You went out.

693
00:42:01.864 --> 00:42:07.327
And you came back
to keep us from killing ourselves.

694
00:42:10.539 --> 00:42:13.167
So if these lines mean
nothing else to you.

695
00:42:14.835 --> 00:42:16.295
well. they mean that to us.

696
00:42:29.183 --> 00:42:32.811
- Let's not have that day again. Okay?
- Yeah.

697
00:42:38.150 --> 00:42:40.235
There are two things
I want to say to you. Hey!

698
00:42:42.529 --> 00:42:45.699
Thing one: That stunt in the market?

699
00:42:46.617 --> 00:42:47.785
Not cool.

700
00:42:48.494 --> 00:42:51.413
I am not the kind of man
who would ever lay hands on a woman.

701
00:42:52.164 --> 00:42:55.667
I honor this badge and my wife.

702
00:42:56.376 --> 00:43:01.006
Yeah. That was a shitty thing to do.
And I'm just not myself right now.

703
00:43:01.632 --> 00:43:02.633
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

704
00:43:03.425 --> 00:43:09.556
Thing two: I've been thinking about
this whole mayoral security thing.

705
00:43:11.266 --> 00:43:13.602
It basically feels like we're treating you
like a prisoner.

706
00:43:15.687 --> 00:43:17.272
And it's not sitting right with me.

707
00:43:19.650 --> 00:43:22.027
Okay. if you wanna get away from all this…

708
00:43:24.613 --> 00:43:27.574
take some time for yourself.
you can tell me.

709
00:43:29.576 --> 00:43:32.496
- I-I'll find a way to make it work.
- What about Camille?

710
00:43:37.084 --> 00:43:38.085
You're my mayor.

711
00:43:39.878 --> 00:43:41.755
You let me worry about Mrs. Sims.

712
00:43:44.883 --> 00:43:46.051
Come on.

713
00:44:12.202 --> 00:44:14.830
You might wanna wear long sleeves
till that heals.

714
00:44:14.913 --> 00:44:17.416
They're looking for a woman
with a damaged right wrist.

715
00:44:20.127 --> 00:44:22.629
I've looked the other way for weeks. Kat.

716
00:44:23.589 --> 00:44:24.715
I haven't put my foot down.

717
00:44:24.798 --> 00:44:26.383
- associating with Kennedy...
- Your foot down?

718
00:44:26.467 --> 00:44:29.386
- You're really gonna go there.
- I don't know where the fuck I'm going.

719
00:44:30.387 --> 00:44:31.555
You saw the page.

720
00:44:31.638 --> 00:44:33.390
The world was beautiful.

721
00:44:33.474 --> 00:44:35.100
You think you need to remind me?

722
00:44:36.727 --> 00:44:40.689
I've spent my whole life
living by something.

723
00:44:40.773 --> 00:44:42.775
enforcing something which is…

724
00:44:42.858 --> 00:44:44.193
- A lie.
- No.

725
00:44:45.736 --> 00:44:46.862
Not all of it.

726
00:44:48.822 --> 00:44:50.407
But if you think there's not a single day

727
00:44:50.491 --> 00:44:54.119
I don't choke on the irony
of being asked to help rewrite the Pact…

728
00:44:55.954 --> 00:44:59.792
How many times do I see the things
that I believed in are wrong?

729
00:45:00.375 --> 00:45:01.960
But what you're doing…

730
00:45:03.921 --> 00:45:08.217
I can't tell you or Kennedy
or anyone else what to think.

731
00:45:08.884 --> 00:45:11.845
But today. things went too far.

732
00:45:11.929 --> 00:45:16.642
Think what you want!
Don't break into IT! Don't grab the mayor!

733
00:45:16.725 --> 00:45:18.352
Your daughter is sleeping.

734
00:45:25.692 --> 00:45:28.362
It's a miracle no one else saw you.

735
00:45:29.988 --> 00:45:33.575
What if they had? What happens then?

736
00:45:33.659 --> 00:45:37.287
When they tell me
my wife is in the middle of this.

737
00:45:38.122 --> 00:45:39.581
I don't know. Paul.

738
00:45:40.165 --> 00:45:42.543
I'm struggling to get a bead
on things too.

739
00:45:45.212 --> 00:45:46.213
[computer beeps]

740
00:46:06.483 --> 00:46:07.651
I gotta go.

741
00:46:09.153 --> 00:46:10.154
Where?

742
00:46:11.697 --> 00:46:12.698
The Mids.

743
00:46:13.907 --> 00:46:15.200
There's a missing person.

744
00:46:17.453 --> 00:46:21.457
[door opens. closes]

745
00:46:25.544 --> 00:46:26.587
Blood pressure's up.

746
00:46:27.838 --> 00:46:29.006
[sighs]

747
00:46:30.090 --> 00:46:32.926
Not surprising
after such a frightening day. right?

748
00:46:33.677 --> 00:46:34.970
Yeah.

749
00:46:35.596 --> 00:46:37.890
- Time for your vitamins.
- Thanks.

750
00:46:50.444 --> 00:46:52.446
- All right. Bye.
- Bye.

751
00:47:09.379 --> 00:47:10.380
[spits]

752
00:47:13.175 --> 00:47:17.012
Hey. Um. I'm gonna go to the cafeteria.
I'm. uh… I'm hungry.

753
00:47:17.513 --> 00:47:18.597
[clears throat]

754
00:47:31.110 --> 00:47:32.486
[sighs]

755
00:47:51.296 --> 00:47:52.756
[Juliette] Never noticed that before.

756
00:47:53.423 --> 00:47:54.883
Yeah. well. now you have.

757
00:47:59.138 --> 00:48:01.014
Ma'am. would you like to order something?

758
00:48:02.099 --> 00:48:04.309
No. I'm good.

759
00:49:22.846 --> 00:49:25.390
On the upside.
I think it gave her a scare.

760
00:49:26.100 --> 00:49:29.228
She apologized for not telling me
about the note straightaway.

761
00:49:29.311 --> 00:49:31.563
[The Algorithm] So you believe
things are back on track.

762
00:49:32.523 --> 00:49:35.609
I can't vouch for tomorrow.
but today. yes.

763
00:49:35.692 --> 00:49:36.693
I think they are.

764
00:49:39.738 --> 00:49:43.826
[The Algorithm] After her return.
Juliette's survival was unwelcome.

765
00:49:44.493 --> 00:49:46.578
But the numbers indicated
it was tolerable.

766
00:49:47.454 --> 00:49:48.956
Perhaps even beneficial.

767
00:49:50.290 --> 00:49:53.377
The blue line represents the calming value
in the Silo

768
00:49:53.460 --> 00:49:55.420
of having Juliette Nichols as mayor.

769
00:49:56.421 --> 00:50:01.343
The red line is the risk she poses
if the memory protocol is not successful.

770
00:50:02.553 --> 00:50:07.433
If those lines cross. Juliette Nichols
will have outlived her usefulness.

771
00:50:08.725 --> 00:50:12.271
The problem. of course.
is that a sudden removal of Juliette

772
00:50:12.354 --> 00:50:15.732
could be catastrophically destabilizing.

773
00:50:17.025 --> 00:50:20.487
We can only hope that the introduction
of the vitamin compound

774
00:50:20.571 --> 00:50:24.116
into the water supply happens
before that becomes necessary.

775
00:50:25.784 --> 00:50:28.036
[metal clanking]
